That's roughly 10^-8 meters long.

So about 400,000 of these nanostructures (the .stl model) could fit in a 4mm needle tip.

title: Kossel Mini Magnetic Diagonal Rod Calibration Jig

description.text:
First off, let me please ask that if you like these designs and find them useful please do like, follow and share my content. And if you have any ideas or concepts to modify the content I would love to hear!

These parts are jigs designed to aid in adjusting the length of the diagonal rods with a 10mm steel ball mounted at the ends. The diagonal rods are used in the Kossel Mini Magnetic Joint Upgrade I have designed ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2343169 ) and simplify the setup calibration process necessary to have the magnetic joint setup work properly as designed.

Just mount the parts to the aluminium extruded profile on your printer using some 4mm bolts and t-nuts (or whatever you can make do with), adjust the length of the rod to the correct length and then glue the threads in place with either some permanent high viscosity thread locking compounding or some Cyanoacrylate (superglue).

I have also added variants of the two parts that allows for the pieces to be mounted in the same location during the entire diagonal rod calibration process. The 10mm ball ends simply clip into place and allow for them to be adjusted accordingly, removed, and then another adjusted within the same jig setup/location.

For calibrating one diagonal rod at a time, print of two of the single cup pieces. For calibrating all at one given point in time, print two of the six cup pieces. Note: Some extra care is necessary when calibrating with the six cup pieces. It is straightforward though and simple to do :)

Be sure to check out the remix offered by LinkerKlinker here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2753434 A neat modification to the design that works really well.

description.text:
This is a little holster for generic thread snips. Snips have a very pointy end so wearing them as a pendant can be a little risky, but they're so handy that people who need them all day usually ignore the risk and do exactly that. This Snips Slipper holds your snips for you with no risk of inadvertent injury or damage to your clothes.

There are three versions:

  1. one with a loop to thread a leather thong or paracord through and wear as a pendant
  2. one with a flat back to use with double-sided tape or just as a loose case
  3. one which holds a 1/2" magnet - this one is handy for sticking to an industrial (steel body) sewing machine or to a steel cabinet.

Regardless of which way the snips slipper is mounted, the snips should hold firm without falling out.

description.text:
One of the photos shows the design evolution I started with Tinkercad and made a simple circle and made some grooves for a lock-washer to fit. I worked but needed more weight.
I then modified it to use 5/16" (12.5mm) nuts and changed it a little to use caps on the nuts it worked better but wasn't perfect. I switched to Fusion 360 and ended up with the final design which by happy accident looks like the 'Nuclear warning symbol' hence the "Nuke Fidget Spinner"

Hole in the center is for a 608 (8x22x7mm) bearing.

June 2 2017
Uploaded a new version of the 608 Bearing caps, I noticed that the originals sometimes would break when trying to insert them fully so I changed the design the new ones work much better.

June 14 2017
added a new file for the 608 caps called 'Nuke Spinner Caps 8.20' these are a big bigger so they fit tighter the original caps were 8.05 mm use what works best for you.

June 4 2017
Changed the Bearing caps slightly again for added strength and changed loading orientation to correct position so they don't have to be rotated also added a full plate version with all the caps and body

Also for those who may not know this, remove the bearing shields and soak the bearings in a degreaser (I use TSP, available in paint section) for 15-20 minutes. Dry and blow out bearings I went from 12-15 second spins to close to a minute spins after performing the cleaning (do not use any lubrication, not needed)

June 4 2017
I also removed the bearing retaining clip (part that holds and centers the balls in the bearing) mine were a plastic of some kind and easy to remove, removing it increased spinning time to 2 minutes!

description.text:
The 'Secret Compartment Box' is just that... a box you can store things in plus a hidden store compartment in the base. The base of the box has a slot through its centre and slides in / out to provide access to the things hidden inside.

Well print 'Secret Compartment Boxes' should look and function like any basic storage box for small things with a lid... to someone 'not expecting' that it is anything other than a basic box they won't notice that the base part can be removed and the floor inside the box is raised a small amount to hide things of value away... a great place to store away things including money, keys, jewellery, notes/letters and more...

A range of 'Secret Compartment Boxes' is provided. The standard box is approx. the size of regular playing cards (65mm x 90mm internal) and 20mm in internal height with the base installed. The base compartment will take things to be hidden up to 5mm thick.

The L and XL are 100mm x 100mm but vary in box height and the base unit height. The L has an internal height of 20mm with a base compartment height of 5mm. The XL has an internal height of 45mm and the base compartment is 10mm (double the height of the other boxes). The L and XL bases are interchangeable.... but using the XL base (10mm internal height) in the L box would greatly reduce the regular internal space too much... which would be more likely to make someone suspect there is a hidden compartment.

The various parts /options are simple prints on well set up machines. The base and lid should be a snug fit into the box part with a fraction of tension as they are slid into place. As not all machines and slicing apps work the same, if your print is tight, uniformly scale it up slightly or scale down uniformly if the fit is too loose.

The 'Secret Compartment Box' is practical for everyday storage of small things.... but also a great way to hide away things of value. Print your box all in one colour or make the lid and box different colours for a brighter / more personalized look.

Great to use yourself at home or work... and a unique gift for friends and family. print one today... and if you do please post images for other members to see.

Please refer to the images and print settings for additional information.

description.text:
The button on my doorbell was cracked and ugly. The wife said, "We got you a 3d printer, why don't you do something useful with it?!?" So, here is my solution. You may want to sand this a bit so the button pushes smoothly.
This fits over my old 22mm, slightly raised, doorbell button. I used double sides foam tape to mount it.
I have published the ball and button together as an STL as well, but the tolerances are too tight for my printer to print them that way.
I published the the OpenJSCAD code if you want to modify this, but it is a little mess. You will need to comment the return lines to get the ball, then the button.

description.text:
A simple to build fishing line stripper to be used with a power drill. Requires a 8mm thread rod and a couple of washers and nuts.
Can be split in two after removing the line from the spool, making it easy to dispose of the old fishing line.

Update:
V3 has a flatter base, making it easier to print. The holes for joining the parts has also been enlarged slightly to accommodate for any inconsistencies when printing.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The current model has a steep angle at the first few layers, I will correct this to make the model nicer and easier to print.

Update:
The V3 models should be easier to print with the flatter base.

Step 1

Cut the threaded rod so it fits through both printed objects and has space for nuts and washers, and a small portion for the drill mount.
Mount two nuts on the drill side with thread lock, and lock them towards each other. Add a washer on the rod.

Step 2

The hole through the two objects is exactly 8mm, and might be a tad smaller after print, or uneven enough that it will be screwed onto the threaded rod, and you'd want it to spin freely.

Easy fix:
Mount the threaded rod with the two nuts on the drill, and while holding one of the two printed objects, thread it, and power the drill until it stops at the washer, then continue running the drill until the threaded rod eats away some plastic inside the hole.

Repeat on the second print, and you should now have two parts that fits snuggly on the rod, but spins freely.

You might have to enlarge the two tine holes on one of the prints, it's 3.1mm while the pins are 3.0, but it's still a bit tight. Just use a 3mm drill bit by hand.
(The V3 version has 3.2mm holes, and should work better).

Step 3

Mount the two prints together and put them on the threaded rod, add a washer and a nut or even better, wing nut and tighten carefully.

Usage:
  • Mount to drill, tie fishing line from your reel, open so the reel spins freely, and power the drill.
  • Cut the line on the reel
  • Remove from drill, and open the nut/wing nut, separate the two printed halves, and remove the line.

Made with Fusion 360. It's basically just two circles in a sketch, the width of the base and the hole. I extruded the base, and used a 60 degree chamfer to make the shape. Then i used fillet to round it off a bit.

This is a box that I designed and had 3D printed (SLS Nylon from 3D Hubs) to hold a 9v battery, a switch and a 5v Adafruit Trinket (which can take up to 16v). It was designed to attached to the rear of my daughter's inline skates in order to run a strip of WS2812B RGB LEDs mounted around the boot.

Edit: This is apparently a very similar design to something called TUSH, so if you wan't more options, just search for 'tush'.

This simple filament holder requires 4 printed parts and 4 ball bearings (ID 6 mm, OD max 20 mm)

There's not much to it; print with your favorite settings, assemble, done.

Notes:

*because the pillars on the male holds all the weight, you might want to go 50%+ infill - just to be on the safe side.

Made this parametric bushing mainly to imitate 608 bearings since 608 bearings are widely used in 3d printing world for parts or toys. 608 bearings also quite expensive depending on where you live (at least my area here are quite expensive too).

This is also a great thing to print because you're able to test your printer's tolerance capability. On my Prusa MK2, printing a single bushing only can go at 0.375mm while printing multiple of them able to go up until 0.3mm

I've included several models to be printed, T350 means Tolerance = 350 micron (0.35mm)

If you've found any bug or want to improve the script, do let me know in the comments section

these are also great to find out your printer's tolerance.
link to test these bushings https://youtu.be/rXqle8XeVQY

Checks

Always check them to ensure that it can rotate at least.

If it can rotate so smoothly, apply WD40 or any similar lube to give it even more spin.

If it is still stuck, try changing the openscad script "tolerance" value higher.

You could also try to use "XY compensation" or "flow rate" in your slicer settings

Parameter Explanation
  • ID - Inner Diameter
  • OD - Outer Diameter
  • W - Width/Thickness (not tested with other combination of parameters yet)
  • Tolerance - tolerance between inner and outer parts as in the gaps
  • chamtype - chamfer type for the middle crevasses
  • cuttype - the placement mode of the crevasses,
  • cham - chamfer distance for the edges
  • Btolerance - To adjust or fine tune the ID and OD
  • margin - Margins between the ID and OD so the crevasse don't cross or always near to this
  • viewmode - view in 2d to check and verify the parameter that has changed
Updates

  • Fixed the crevasse not following the W parameter correctly, Now you can go as thick/wide as you want
  • Added GAC constant to avoid error below. Best not to change this

description.text: This thing is a printable ratcheting pulley block, designed for 550lb Paracord (other 1/8 inch or ~3.0 mm rope will likely work too, but I have only tried paracord). It allows you to easily raise and lower a hanging object. To see exactly what this thing does, please watch this short video... VIDEO---> http://flic.kr/p/c4ujHG

GENERAL:
The Paracord Ratchet works for me right off the print bed without any clean-up. I have been printing these in PLA with 20% infill and three extra shells on all layers. All the stress at the holes is radial to the axles, so I figured it's best to have a few layers around each hole for reinforcement. I also recommend printing the solid sides of the housing 100% filled, in Skeinforge 41 (which I am still using :P) I do this by setting the solid surface thickness layers to 4. With a layer height of .28 mm, this guarantees the 2.0 mm sides will print solid while other sections will have 20% fill. Note: The file RatchetSolidWorks.zip contains the SolidWorks files for all five parts. ASSEMBLY:
Assemble using 4-40 x 1.0 inch bolts (x5) with 4-40 lock nuts (x5) or M3 x 25 mm bolts (x5) with M3 lock nuts (x5). If you don't have lock nuts, you can use jam nuts (two regular nuts locked together). The lock nuts are necessary for proper functionality, the wheel axle and release pivot nuts need to be slightly loose so they don't pinch the housing and restrict component rotation. They should be tightened so they just barely touch the housing. Regular nuts will spin off the bolts when the ratchet is in use. Lock-tite or super-glue can also be used also to secure standard nuts in the proper position. The three bolts that hold the housing together should be fully tightened. A spring or rubber-band is also necessary for this thing to work properly. I picked up a few small extension springs from the local hardware store, the one in the pictures is about 9.0 mm long (coil end to end, not including the hanging loops) and about 6.0 mm in diameter. See the photos for one possible rubber-band configuration option. There only needs to be light tension, so just about any spring or rubber-band that fits will work. HOW TO USE:
To use this thing, first attach one end of your paracord to your secure hanging point. Then thread the other end down through the opening on the top of the Paracord Ratchet, and down the side of the wheel where the housing is open. While holding the release lever down (not necessary but it makes it easier), turn the wheel and paracord together until the paracord travels around the wheels and comes out the top again. It may be necessary to use needle nose pliers or something to guide the end of the cord out. Once the end of the cord is coming back out the top, it is ready to use. See the video link above for a short demonstration of the Paracord Ratchet in use.
IMPORTANT: Test your ratchet to make sure it operates properly before hanging anything from it!

  • Many 3D printer hot ends contain materials that are certainly not food safe. ... So if you are not using an all stainless steel hot end, trace amounts of nasties could find their way from your printer hot end, into your model and eventually into your food.
  • Most PLA is coloured. So other additives have been added to your PLA to give it a funky colour. If you are printing things that contact foods, you should stick with ‘virgin’ or ‘natural’ PLA.
  • It is going to be near impossible to keep your printed objects clean. 3D prints are covered with nooks and crannies. ... These little pores, when filled with food are a fertile breading ground for bacteria ... .

description.text:
I remixed the following parts for my lightsaber make:

Ribs: shaved .4mm off the bottom and lengthened 2mm
Body: added a 4mm X 26mm slot for my button design
Crystal: ran thru netfab to clean it up
Button: created a button that slides in the slot

I printed the button at .1 layer, 100% fill.
First I printed Button1 in silver.
Then I started printing Button2 in red with a pause at .4mm to change to black.
Also, Button1 is 1mm thick with a .4mm inset, so to get the red to go down in I added the following start gcode: "G92 Z-0.6" right after the "G28 Z0 ;move Z to min endstops" which makes it move up .6mm. Hope that makes sense!

Button3 can be printed as is and inserted thru the bottom, or you can scale it up and press it in the other way. I printed mine out of ninjaflex at 110% scale.

Button4 is just Button1 and Button2 merged together.

title: 1 DIN car stereo faceplate for 12v power sockets

description.text:
This is designed to fit into a standard 1 DIN (180x50cm) size car stereo space. My car has a 2 DIN space but only a 1 DIN radio, and the "filler" panel there was just taking up space so I decided to make it useful by putting two extra 12v sockets in it.
Holes are 30mm so should fit most 12v sockets.
Front is flared 2mm for better installation appearance and to keep the piece from pushing back inside the hole.
If I were to spend time improving the design (or maybe you feel like making a derivative?) I would put some sort of tabs on the edges so that it snaps into place. Friction seems to keep it in just fine, at first I used doublesided tape to keep it in but it was unnecessary.

Needs no special treatment. I did mine 25% infill but could probably be set with less for faster printing, due to the thin nature of the walls. The whole piece ends up solid anyways.
I recommend printing in ABS to prevent melting/warping if your car sits in the sun.
